'''Japan's Three Great Vengeful Spirits''' (日本三大怨霊, Nihon Sandai Onryō) refers to three specific vengeful spirits in Japan: {{ill|Sugawara no Michizane|ja|Sugawara no Michizane|12=draft}}, {{ill|Taira no Masakado|ja|Taira no Masakado|1=Taira no Masakado|12=draft}}, and {{ill|Emperor Sutoku|ja|崇徳天皇|12=draft}}.<ref>{{cite video|和書|people=Hirofumi Yamamoto|date=2017-01-25|title=Super Fast!! Frugal!? The Front and Back of Daimyo Processions: The Mysteries and Wonders of Sankin Kōtai|medium=E-book|language=Japanese|publisher=Jitsugyo no Nihon Sha}}</ref> Historian {{ill|Yūji Yamada|ja|山田雄司|12=draft}} argues that the perception of Sugawara no Michizane, Taira no Masakado, and Emperor Sutoku as the Three Great Vengeful Spirits was largely shaped by {{ill|yomihon|ja|読本|12=draft}}, {{ill|kabuki|ja|歌舞伎|12=draft}}, and other cultural influences during the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|12=draft}}.{{sfn|Yamada Yūji|2014|at=Preface}}

